23
00:02:10,391 --> 00:02:11,740
No, I'm not.

24
00:02:11,783 --> 00:02:12,828
Come on, lunchtime.

25
00:02:22,490 --> 00:02:23,969
You are such a thief.

26
00:02:26,058 --> 00:02:27,103
You want a sandwich?

27
00:02:27,147 --> 00:02:28,626
You're making lunch? Sure.

28
00:02:30,193 --> 00:02:31,673
[DOORBELL RINGS]

29
00:02:43,989 --> 00:02:45,252
Hello.

30
00:02:45,295 --> 00:02:46,862
Hello. Is your mother home?

31
00:02:48,733 --> 00:02:50,082
Who are you?

32
00:02:50,126 --> 00:02:51,736
I've come...

33
00:02:51,780 --> 00:02:54,174
I'd like to interview
for the nanny position.

34
00:02:54,870 --> 00:02:55,871
The nanny.

35
00:02:56,524 --> 00:02:58,743
Okay, um...

36
00:02:58,787 --> 00:03:00,484
[STAMMERS]
Um, well, I tried to call
but the number was busy

37
00:03:00,528 --> 00:03:02,660
and the address
was on here.

38
00:03:04,009 --> 00:03:05,402
I think you'd better
talk to my dad.

39
00:03:05,446 --> 00:03:06,447
Come in.

40
00:03:08,710 --> 00:03:10,233
You sound like
Mary Poppins.

41
00:03:10,277 --> 00:03:11,234
I'm English.

42
00:03:11,278 --> 00:03:12,844
I knew that.

43
00:03:12,888 --> 00:03:14,106
SAM: Who's she?

44
00:03:14,150 --> 00:03:16,370
That's Sam.Hi, Sam.

45
00:03:16,413 --> 00:03:17,501
I start school tomorrow.

46
00:03:17,545 --> 00:03:19,547
I'm four.

47
00:03:19,590 --> 00:03:21,810
How wonderful.
I'm Gillian.

48
00:03:21,853 --> 00:03:23,203
And I'm Doc.

49
00:03:23,246 --> 00:03:24,813
That's short for Rebecca.

50
00:03:24,856 --> 00:03:25,988
I'm 10.

51
00:03:26,031 --> 00:03:27,032
Hi, Doc.

52
00:03:27,076 --> 00:03:28,251
Hi.

53
00:03:28,295 --> 00:03:29,731
She's a nanny.

54
00:03:29,774 --> 00:03:31,907
You know, like
Mary Poppins.

55
00:03:31,950 --> 00:03:33,256
Where's your umbrella?

56
00:03:33,300 --> 00:03:35,345
[LAUGHS] It's in my case.

57
00:03:35,389 --> 00:03:36,738
Come on. Dad's this way.

58
00:03:40,394 --> 00:03:42,222
Hey, Dad,
she's a nanny!

59
00:03:43,788 --> 00:03:45,181
Uh, hello.

60
00:03:45,225 --> 00:03:47,879
Hello. I'm Gillian Malkin.

61
00:03:47,923 --> 00:03:49,968
I was hoping to interview
for the nanny.

62
00:03:50,012 --> 00:03:51,883
She knows Mary Poppins.

63
00:03:51,927 --> 00:03:53,320
Really?

64
00:03:53,363 --> 00:03:56,192
I'm sorry,
I, I did try to call.

65
00:03:56,236 --> 00:03:58,629
And you know Barney.
Come on, feeding time.

66
00:04:00,588 --> 00:04:01,502
Good luck.

67
00:04:02,372 --> 00:04:04,069
[CHUCKLES]

68
00:04:04,113 --> 00:04:06,289
Don't you just hate
precocious American kids?

69
00:04:06,333 --> 00:04:08,770
Oh, not yet.
This is my first interview.

70
00:04:08,813 --> 00:04:10,728
I keep forgetting
to break her will.

71
00:04:10,772 --> 00:04:13,644
I beg your pardon?My kid...

72
00:04:13,688 --> 00:04:15,385
Break her spirit.
Like breaking a horse?

73
00:04:16,386 --> 00:04:17,953
It's a joke.

74
00:04:17,996 --> 00:04:21,086
Oh, I'm sorry, the notice said
you wanted a sense of humor.

75
00:04:21,130 --> 00:04:23,132
It's okay, my wife's got
the sense of humor.

76
00:04:23,175 --> 00:04:24,176
I keep trying.

77
00:04:25,352 --> 00:04:26,875
She's not home.

78
00:04:26,918 --> 00:04:28,877
Oh, should I come
another time?

79
00:04:28,920 --> 00:04:31,532
DOC: Dad, you want me
to show her the house?

80
00:04:32,924 --> 00:04:34,274
Where would I be
without her? [CHUCKLES]

81
00:04:39,757 --> 00:04:41,846
[SIGHS] Oh, what
a wonderful room.

82
00:04:41,890 --> 00:04:43,021
Mmm.

83
00:04:45,937 --> 00:04:47,112
[SIGHS]

84
00:04:47,156 --> 00:04:49,332
This is so wonderful.

85
00:04:49,376 --> 00:04:51,160
[CHUCKLES]
I keep saying that.

86
00:04:51,203 --> 00:04:53,118
It's okay. Originality is only
5% of the grade.

87
00:04:53,162 --> 00:04:55,033
[CHUCKLES]

88
00:04:55,077 --> 00:04:57,297
Do you have a, a cook,
or a housekeeper?

89
00:04:57,340 --> 00:04:58,298
Annie.

90
00:05:04,608 --> 00:05:07,611
And, uh, this is the, uh,

91
00:05:08,395 --> 00:05:10,135
uh, nanny's room.

92
00:05:10,179 --> 00:05:12,790
This is so lovely.

93
00:05:12,834 --> 00:05:14,923
When did your
nanny leave?

94
00:05:14,966 --> 00:05:16,620
She didn't.
We never had one.

95
00:05:20,929 --> 00:05:22,278
TIM: The most difficult
part of the job

96
00:05:22,322 --> 00:05:24,367
will be taking care
of our daughter.

97
00:05:24,411 --> 00:05:25,716
Oh, no,
Rebecca's delightful.

98
00:05:25,760 --> 00:05:27,805
Not Doc.
Our other daughter.

99
00:05:27,849 --> 00:05:29,198
Oh, she must be
out with your wife.

100
00:05:29,241 --> 00:05:30,591
Should I wait...She's not out.

101
00:05:31,679 --> 00:05:33,507
Asleep?She's not home.

102
00:05:36,727 --> 00:05:38,076
Our other daughter
is Maggie.

103
00:05:39,208 --> 00:05:42,037
She's five years old

104
00:05:42,080 --> 00:05:45,475
and she exists only
in the mind of my wife.

105
00:05:45,519 --> 00:05:47,695
Miss Malkin, if you think
you might want this job

106
00:05:47,738 --> 00:05:51,438
I want you to know
how seriously I take
the subject of Maggie.

107
00:05:51,481 --> 00:05:53,048
She's the most important
part of your job.

108
00:05:56,921 --> 00:05:59,010
Maggie.

109
00:05:59,054 --> 00:06:00,360
DOC: Let's go see
if she's still here.

110
00:06:00,403 --> 00:06:02,971
SAM: Okay.

111
00:06:03,014 --> 00:06:05,408
You've been talking
about my sister.

112
00:06:05,452 --> 00:06:07,149
SAM: Maggie's out with Mom.

113
00:06:07,192 --> 00:06:09,456
Maggie starts
kindergarten tomorrow.

114
00:06:09,499 --> 00:06:11,371
I start pre-school.

115
00:06:11,414 --> 00:06:12,676
That's nice.

116
00:06:12,720 --> 00:06:14,417
Doc, don't you and Sam
have something to do?

117
00:06:14,461 --> 00:06:16,027
Come on, Sam.

118
00:06:16,071 --> 00:06:19,248
I want to see how hard
I can hit you with the ball.

119
00:06:19,291 --> 00:06:22,033
Doc's going to teach me and
Maggie how to play catch.

120
00:06:23,644 --> 00:06:25,036
I hope you take the job

121
00:06:25,080 --> 00:06:26,516
'cause I could
use some help.

122
00:06:32,217 --> 00:06:35,177
I'm afraid that I...
I don't understand.

123
00:06:35,220 --> 00:06:36,744
I'd be amazed if you did.

124
00:06:38,702 --> 00:06:41,139
Maggie is five years old.
Sam is four.

125
00:06:41,183 --> 00:06:44,447
Sam thinks he has
an invisible sister.

126
00:06:44,491 --> 00:06:46,623
Annie thinks she has
a 5-year-old daughter.

127
00:06:48,495 --> 00:06:50,192
Doc and I pretend
to see her.

128
00:06:52,107 --> 00:06:53,630
[CAR HORN HONKS]

129
00:06:53,674 --> 00:06:55,066
[CAR APPROACHING]

130
00:06:55,110 --> 00:06:56,067
That's Annie.

131
00:07:04,206 --> 00:07:07,035
[BOTH SPEAK INDISTINCTLY]

132
00:07:07,078 --> 00:07:08,602
DOC: There you go.
Be careful.

133
00:07:08,645 --> 00:07:10,473
[DOC AND SAM LAUGHING]

134
00:07:13,476 --> 00:07:15,435
[SOFTLY] Hi.

135
00:07:15,478 --> 00:07:16,261
Hi, Mom!

136
00:07:16,305 --> 00:07:17,437
Look, look!

137
00:07:20,178 --> 00:07:21,441
ANNIE: Aw...

138
00:07:22,442 --> 00:07:24,139
[GIGGLES] Hey.

139
00:07:24,182 --> 00:07:25,880
Hey, Mom.Hi, guys, how are you?

140
00:07:28,535 --> 00:07:30,101
Beautiful day, huh?Yeah.

141
00:07:30,145 --> 00:07:31,494
Oh, I got lipstick
on you. Sorry.[GIGGLES] That's okay.

142
00:07:32,974 --> 00:07:34,105
Sweetheart.

143
00:07:36,281 --> 00:07:37,587
This is Gillian.

144
00:07:37,631 --> 00:07:39,110
I know.

145
00:07:39,154 --> 00:07:41,809
Doc and Sam were raving
about you outside.

146
00:07:41,852 --> 00:07:43,506
Well, Doc's right.

147
00:07:43,550 --> 00:07:44,594
You're wonderful.

148
00:07:45,552 --> 00:07:46,640
Oh...

149
00:07:50,818 --> 00:07:52,384
You're perfect. [CHUCKLES]

150
00:07:52,428 --> 00:07:54,038
Perfect?

151
00:07:54,082 --> 00:07:55,823
Oh, yes. I just put up
the notice today

152
00:07:55,866 --> 00:07:57,215
and you're the
first to come.

153
00:07:57,259 --> 00:07:58,521
Oh, I see.

154
00:07:58,565 --> 00:08:00,218
And you're so
far from home.

155
00:08:00,262 --> 00:08:02,525
You're very brave,
isn't she, Tim?

156
00:08:02,569 --> 00:08:03,352
She certainly is.

157
00:08:06,442 --> 00:08:09,010
Well, you won't
be lonely with us.

158
00:08:09,053 --> 00:08:11,665
Look, I don't have
any references.

159
00:08:11,708 --> 00:08:14,145
I've never been
a nanny before.

160
00:08:14,189 --> 00:08:17,279
But I raised all
my younger brothers
and sisters.

161
00:08:17,322 --> 00:08:19,368
The youngest just turned 15.

162
00:08:19,411 --> 00:08:22,545
Um, my mum's been
kind of sick, you see,
for a long time.

163
00:08:26,070 --> 00:08:28,682
You're perfect.

164
00:08:28,725 --> 00:08:30,553
And I'm glad that
you don't have any
references

165
00:08:30,597 --> 00:08:32,163
because we've
never had a nanny

166
00:08:32,207 --> 00:08:33,861
and you've never been one,
so we'll learn together.

167
00:08:33,904 --> 00:08:34,949
[CHUCKLES]

168
00:08:34,992 --> 00:08:36,167
Isn't that right, honey?

169
00:08:36,211 --> 00:08:37,734
Sure. Uh, Annie...

170
00:08:37,778 --> 00:08:40,650
It's $400 a week.
Plus room and board

171
00:08:40,694 --> 00:08:42,522
and use of a car and
two days off, of course.

172
00:08:42,565 --> 00:08:43,740
Oh, that's...

173
00:08:45,350 --> 00:08:47,352
But maybe you want
to discuss this.

174
00:08:47,396 --> 00:08:49,485
Annie, why don't we,
uh, give Gillian a call

175
00:08:49,529 --> 00:08:51,574
in a day or two,
let her know.

176
00:08:51,618 --> 00:08:54,577
And she probably wants
to think about it too.
Don't you, Gillian?

177
00:08:54,621 --> 00:08:55,796
Oh, but, honey,
she just arrived.

178
00:08:55,839 --> 00:08:57,232
She has no place to stay.

179
00:08:57,972 --> 00:09:00,278
Do you?

180
00:09:00,322 --> 00:09:02,324
Your car in the driveway,
it's full of suitcases.

181
00:09:02,367 --> 00:09:03,368
Oh.

182
00:09:04,631 --> 00:09:06,110
She knows Mary Poppins!Oh.

183
00:09:07,329 --> 00:09:09,331
[LAUGHS]

184
00:09:09,374 --> 00:09:11,986
Maggie.
This is Gillian.

185
00:09:12,029 --> 00:09:13,553
Gillian, this is Maggie.

186
00:09:17,557 --> 00:09:19,123
Hello, Maggie.

187
00:09:19,167 --> 00:09:20,603
It's nice to meet you.

188
00:09:25,129 --> 00:09:26,696
Did you leave the front
door open again?

189
00:09:26,740 --> 00:09:28,480
I'll do it.Oh.

190
00:09:28,524 --> 00:09:29,612
Kids, don't run.

191
00:09:29,656 --> 00:09:30,657
Oh!

192
00:09:32,354 --> 00:09:34,617
Well, did Tim
show you your room?

193
00:09:34,661 --> 00:09:35,879
Yes, he did.Is it all right?

194
00:09:35,923 --> 00:09:37,620
Oh, it's wonderful.

195
00:09:37,664 --> 00:09:40,014
Good.
Then it's settled.

196
00:09:40,057 --> 00:09:42,320
Um, okay, well,
Doc you help me
unload the car.

197
00:09:42,364 --> 00:09:44,627
And, uh, Gillian,
you'll want to unpack.

198
00:09:44,671 --> 00:09:46,455
And just let us know if
you need anything, okay?

199
00:09:46,498 --> 00:09:47,238
Okay.

200
00:09:50,415 --> 00:09:51,591
Is this all right?

201
00:09:52,504 --> 00:09:54,071
Welcome to the family.

202
00:09:55,029 --> 00:09:55,899
[SIGHS]

203
00:10:07,215 --> 00:10:08,912
Are you unpacked?Mmm-hmm.

204
00:10:10,305 --> 00:10:11,654
DOC: Do you like it here?

205
00:10:11,698 --> 00:10:14,309
Oh, it's like a dream.

206
00:10:14,352 --> 00:10:16,137
Do you live in the
country in England?

207
00:10:16,180 --> 00:10:17,791
No, London.

208
00:10:17,834 --> 00:10:19,053
Big city, huh?

209
00:10:19,096 --> 00:10:21,272
Hey, you forgot to push.

210
00:10:21,316 --> 00:10:22,709
Come on, you don't hear
Maggie complaining.

211
00:10:22,752 --> 00:10:26,147
SAM: Yes, I do.
Especially about vegetables.

212
00:10:26,190 --> 00:10:27,714
DOC: Okay, come on,
Maggie, no hitting.

213
00:10:28,976 --> 00:10:29,977
[GRUNTS]

214
00:10:30,455 --> 00:10:31,848
Stop it, Sam.

215
00:10:31,892 --> 00:10:34,024
SAM: She punched first.

216
00:10:34,068 --> 00:10:35,504
Sometimes you gotta
separate these two.

217
00:10:37,462 --> 00:10:39,421
You mind pushing
Maggie a while?

218
00:10:39,464 --> 00:10:41,771
Um, no.

219
00:10:41,815 --> 00:10:42,903
Thanks. Come on, Sam.

220
00:11:00,790 --> 00:11:02,096
What are you doing?

221
00:11:03,010 --> 00:11:05,360
Pushing Maggie.

222
00:11:05,403 --> 00:11:06,927
Maggie's in her
room taking a nap.

223
00:11:09,886 --> 00:11:11,540
Your father told me.

224
00:11:11,583 --> 00:11:13,150
That I know
Maggie's not real?

225
00:11:13,194 --> 00:11:14,978
Mmm-hmm.Right.

226
00:11:15,457 --> 00:11:16,588
I do.

227
00:11:17,764 --> 00:11:19,113
She takes a lot of naps.

228
00:11:20,984 --> 00:11:23,030
And how does one know?

229
00:11:23,073 --> 00:11:24,553
You don't always know.

230
00:11:32,779 --> 00:11:35,433
Um, Gillian, why don't you
sit here next to Maggie?

231
00:11:36,913 --> 00:11:38,393
Sam, Maggie, dinner.

232
00:11:39,786 --> 00:11:41,439
Sam, did you
two wash up?

233
00:11:41,483 --> 00:11:44,138
I did. Maggie didn't.

234
00:11:44,181 --> 00:11:45,792
I know you did.
He's just teasing.

235
00:11:45,835 --> 00:11:47,619
Mmm... [SLURPS]

236
00:11:47,663 --> 00:11:49,621
Mashed potatoes
are my favorite.

237
00:11:52,886 --> 00:11:55,018
Maggie, would you say grace?

238
00:12:08,031 --> 00:12:09,337
ANNIE: Amen.ALL: Amen.

239
00:12:11,861 --> 00:12:13,733
Doc's stealing Maggie's food.

240
00:12:13,776 --> 00:12:15,299
I was cutting her broccoli.

241
00:12:15,343 --> 00:12:17,127
Oh, okay.
Sam, eat your own food.

242
00:12:17,171 --> 00:12:19,564
Don't worry about
Maggie and Doc.

243
00:12:19,608 --> 00:12:21,088
So, you come
from a large family?

244
00:12:22,002 --> 00:12:23,873
Um, five kids.

245
00:12:23,917 --> 00:12:25,396
I'm the eldest. Thanks.

246
00:12:25,440 --> 00:12:26,920
And you raised the others?

247
00:12:26,963 --> 00:12:28,225
My mum couldn't, you see.

248
00:12:28,269 --> 00:12:29,923
And my dad passed
away years ago.

249
00:12:31,011 --> 00:12:32,752
What's, "passed away?"

250
00:12:32,795 --> 00:12:34,101
Died.

251
00:12:34,144 --> 00:12:35,885
Her daddy is with the angels.

252
00:12:37,582 --> 00:12:39,062
How old were you when
your mom got sick?

253
00:12:40,716 --> 00:12:42,500
I was about 10.

254
00:12:42,544 --> 00:12:44,807
And you stayed until
the youngest could take
care of themselves?

255
00:12:46,156 --> 00:12:47,592
That's very unselfish.

256
00:12:48,550 --> 00:12:50,421
You postponed yourself.

257
00:12:50,465 --> 00:12:52,119
Honey, she may not want
to talk about this now.

258
00:12:52,162 --> 00:12:54,556
GILLIAN: No, it, it's fine.

259
00:12:54,599 --> 00:12:59,039
Um, I wouldn't say
I was unselfish or
anything that grand.

260
00:12:59,082 --> 00:13:01,128
Of course not, but you are.

261
00:13:01,171 --> 00:13:03,173
And now it's your turn.

262
00:13:03,217 --> 00:13:04,827
I'm sure your
mother agrees.

263
00:13:04,871 --> 00:13:06,089
What's her name?

264
00:13:07,874 --> 00:13:09,658
Emma.

265
00:13:09,701 --> 00:13:11,399
Emma.

266
00:13:11,442 --> 00:13:12,617
Have you called her to let
her know that you're here?

267
00:13:13,488 --> 00:13:14,619
No.

268
00:13:14,663 --> 00:13:16,752
Oh, well, let's call
her right now.

269
00:13:16,796 --> 00:13:18,188
Honey, it's about
3:00 am there.

270
00:13:18,232 --> 00:13:20,408
Oh, that's right. [CHUCKLES]

271
00:13:20,451 --> 00:13:22,366
Well, please call her
first thing in the morning

272
00:13:22,410 --> 00:13:24,673
and let her know that
she can call you collect
whenever she misses you.

273
00:13:26,240 --> 00:13:27,545
That's very nice, but...

274
00:13:27,589 --> 00:13:29,634
You haven't been away
from home, have you?

275
00:13:29,678 --> 00:13:31,288
Um...

276
00:13:31,332 --> 00:13:33,073
I went to Loch Ness once.

277
00:13:33,116 --> 00:13:34,509
[CHUCKLES]Ooh.

278
00:13:34,552 --> 00:13:36,119
[DOC LAUGHS][SHUSHING]

279
00:13:43,823 --> 00:13:45,172
Hold still.

280
00:13:47,000 --> 00:13:48,088
It's an eyelash.

281
00:13:48,958 --> 00:13:50,090
ANNIE: Okay?

282
00:13:51,918 --> 00:13:55,225
I got it. See?

283
00:13:55,269 --> 00:13:57,488
Now it's good luck.
You got to make a wish
and blow it away.

284
00:13:59,839 --> 00:14:01,492
Oh, no, come in.

285
00:14:01,536 --> 00:14:03,538
This is a busy time.
I've got to put Sam to bed.

286
00:14:03,581 --> 00:14:06,758
You give Maggie her bath.
She'll tell you where
everything is.

287
00:14:06,802 --> 00:14:09,283
Maggie, you can take a
tubby in Mommy's bath.

288
00:14:09,326 --> 00:14:10,675
[CHUCKLES]

289
00:14:10,719 --> 00:14:13,678
Well, she's learning.
We've got to help her out.

290
00:14:13,722 --> 00:14:16,594
All right, um, she likes
the water a little hotter
than warm.

291
00:14:22,513 --> 00:14:23,819
[GRUNTS]

292
00:14:23,863 --> 00:14:26,169
It's been an interesting day.

293
00:14:26,213 --> 00:14:28,215
Oh, I don't know. You think?

294
00:14:31,609 --> 00:14:33,394
Why did Mom do this?I don't know.

295
00:14:35,178 --> 00:14:36,919
Me either.

296
00:14:36,963 --> 00:14:39,269
You have that look.What look?

297
00:14:39,313 --> 00:14:40,967
Your crinkly look.

298
00:14:41,010 --> 00:14:42,142
I have that?

299
00:14:45,014 --> 00:14:46,581
I don't know
why Mom did this.

300
00:14:46,624 --> 00:14:48,191
I don't know if
Gillian can handle it.

301
00:14:48,235 --> 00:14:49,845
It's a lot to ask
of somebody.

302
00:14:49,889 --> 00:14:51,325
Why do we need her?

303
00:14:51,368 --> 00:14:53,631
Mom does everything
for Maggie anyway.

304
00:14:53,675 --> 00:14:56,634
We have to trust
there's a good reason.

305
00:14:56,678 --> 00:14:59,986
Like we trust there's a
good reason for Maggie?

306
00:15:00,029 --> 00:15:02,031
Exactly.
Like we do that.

307
00:15:04,033 --> 00:15:05,992
People grow
and change, Doc.

308
00:15:06,035 --> 00:15:07,950
Even parents.

309
00:15:07,994 --> 00:15:09,343
Nothing stays
the same forever.

310
00:15:11,040 --> 00:15:12,650
Sweet dreams.

311
00:15:12,694 --> 00:15:14,000
I love you.I love you, too.

312
00:15:24,749 --> 00:15:28,275
All right, you can stay
in a couple more minutes.

313
00:15:28,318 --> 00:15:31,017
GILLIAN: That's right.
Tomorrow's a big day.

314
00:15:31,060 --> 00:15:34,890
First days are a little scary
but it'll be fun, I think.

315
00:15:34,934 --> 00:15:38,502
Once you get there
you'll meet lots
of new children

316
00:15:38,546 --> 00:15:40,678
and, and there will
be lots of new toys

317
00:15:40,722 --> 00:15:43,899
and things to play with.

318
00:15:43,943 --> 00:15:46,597
Oh, um, did I get
soap in your eye?

319
00:15:46,641 --> 00:15:48,251
Oh, good. I, I thought I did.

320
00:15:50,514 --> 00:15:52,212
I went out to the
museum site today.

321
00:15:53,126 --> 00:15:55,867
Without me? You rat.

322
00:15:55,911 --> 00:15:57,608
So, what did you think?

323
00:15:57,652 --> 00:16:00,960
Well, all those
skinny columns, um...

324
00:16:01,003 --> 00:16:03,005
It looks kind of like
a giant bicycle rack.

325
00:16:05,834 --> 00:16:07,967
I'm kidding,
it's breathtaking.

326
00:16:08,010 --> 00:16:09,403
Really.

327
00:16:09,446 --> 00:16:10,882
A bicycle rack?

328
00:16:12,667 --> 00:16:14,495
[CHUCKLES] So,
what do you think?

329
00:16:14,538 --> 00:16:16,279
It's intentional,
I like bicycle racks.

330
00:16:16,323 --> 00:16:17,324
Of Gillian.

331
00:16:18,847 --> 00:16:20,414
She'll be great.

332
00:16:21,458 --> 00:16:25,027
I'm sorry I surprised you.

333
00:16:25,071 --> 00:16:27,247
I was going to interview
a few before I said anything

334
00:16:27,290 --> 00:16:31,773
'cause, maybe I wouldn't
find the right person

335
00:16:31,816 --> 00:16:34,819
or maybe I would
change my mind.

336
00:16:34,863 --> 00:16:36,343
I had no idea
you wanted help.

337
00:16:37,779 --> 00:16:39,911
It just seemed
time, I guess.

338
00:16:39,955 --> 00:16:41,565
I mean, you've
been so patient.

339
00:16:42,784 --> 00:16:45,221
I thought we
could use somebody.

340
00:16:45,265 --> 00:16:48,137
Then maybe you wouldn't have
to work at home so much

341
00:16:48,181 --> 00:16:50,183
and you could go
back to your office,

342
00:16:50,226 --> 00:16:51,314
if it's still there.

343
00:16:52,141 --> 00:16:54,274
Wow.

344
00:16:54,317 --> 00:16:57,407
Have I been complaining,
'cause I'm fine, really.

345
00:16:58,669 --> 00:16:59,888
You never complain.

346
00:17:03,326 --> 00:17:06,068
Is everything okay?Sure.

347
00:17:06,112 --> 00:17:08,375
And Gillian will be fine,
once she settles in.

348
00:17:19,690 --> 00:17:20,735
[GROANS]

349
00:17:24,695 --> 00:17:25,783
Oh, well.

350
00:17:29,309 --> 00:17:30,658
Okay, Maggie, your turn.

351
00:17:48,284 --> 00:17:49,590
You'll wear this.

352
00:17:52,419 --> 00:17:53,594
And these.

353
00:17:55,378 --> 00:17:56,684
And these shoes.

354
00:18:14,093 --> 00:18:16,007
ANNIE: I usually give Maggie
peanut butter and jelly.

355
00:18:16,051 --> 00:18:18,836
Sam gets milk,
Maggie gets juice.

356
00:18:18,880 --> 00:18:20,316
And Doc?

357
00:18:20,360 --> 00:18:22,144
She makes her own because
she has to get ready first

358
00:18:22,188 --> 00:18:22,971
so she can catch the bus.

359
00:18:23,014 --> 00:18:24,277
TIM: Okay.

360
00:18:24,320 --> 00:18:25,974
Okay, Sam,
Maggie, let's go.

361
00:18:26,017 --> 00:18:27,323
No, Tim.

362
00:18:27,367 --> 00:18:28,890
We have a nanny now.

363
00:18:28,933 --> 00:18:30,109
Gillian will drive them.

364
00:18:30,152 --> 00:18:31,936
Well, I always
drove Maggie.

365
00:18:31,980 --> 00:18:34,504
I know you did.
But now we have Gillian.

366
00:18:34,548 --> 00:18:35,897
How do we know
she can drive?

367
00:18:35,940 --> 00:18:37,420
Because I drove with
her this morning.

368
00:18:37,464 --> 00:18:38,639
She did fine.

369
00:18:38,682 --> 00:18:40,597
You drove this morning?Yeah, early.

370
00:18:40,641 --> 00:18:41,859
How's she going
to find the school?

371
00:18:41,903 --> 00:18:43,513
Don't forget
to eat Maggie's lunch.

372
00:18:43,557 --> 00:18:45,428
That's what Dad did.Thanks.

373
00:18:45,472 --> 00:18:47,604
Okay, Doc, I'm going
to drop you at the bus.

374
00:18:49,432 --> 00:18:50,564
Have fun, you two.

375
00:18:52,653 --> 00:18:53,567
Hey.

376
00:19:03,794 --> 00:19:05,535
You are so beautiful.

377
00:19:06,754 --> 00:19:07,581
I bet.

378
00:19:11,106 --> 00:19:12,455
Okay.

379
00:19:12,499 --> 00:19:13,630
Bye.Bye.

380
00:19:18,026 --> 00:19:20,115
[EXHALES] Ready?

381
00:19:22,944 --> 00:19:25,599
All right, the school...

382
00:19:25,642 --> 00:19:27,731
First day, Maggie. Let's go.

383
00:19:35,086 --> 00:19:37,393
ANNIE: They should be
getting out any minute.

384
00:19:37,437 --> 00:19:38,786
GILLIAN:
I could have done this.

385
00:19:38,829 --> 00:19:41,789
I know, but it's Sam's
first day of school

386
00:19:41,832 --> 00:19:43,486
and I've never
had a nanny before.

387
00:19:43,530 --> 00:19:45,184
I guess I have
to ease into this.

388
00:19:45,227 --> 00:19:46,010
Of course.

389
00:19:46,054 --> 00:19:47,751
[SIGHS]

390
00:19:47,795 --> 00:19:50,101
You know, if you want to go
and talk to your friends...

391
00:19:50,145 --> 00:19:51,799
No, that's okay.[SCHOOL BELL RINGING]

392
00:19:51,842 --> 00:19:53,627
Tim always drove
Maggie to school.

393
00:19:53,670 --> 00:19:55,411
I don't really
know anybody.

394
00:19:55,455 --> 00:19:57,283
WOMAN: Bye, children,
see you tomorrow.

395
00:19:58,458 --> 00:19:59,937
[INDISTINCT CHATTER]

396
00:20:06,205 --> 00:20:08,076
Hi, hi, hi.

397
00:20:08,119 --> 00:20:10,252
How was your
day at school?

398
00:20:10,296 --> 00:20:11,514
Good.Do you like
your teacher?

399
00:20:11,558 --> 00:20:12,863
SAM: She's nice.

400
00:20:12,907 --> 00:20:14,256
I made you something
in school today.

401
00:20:15,649 --> 00:20:16,737
You made this?

402
00:20:16,780 --> 00:20:18,086
They have a machine.

403
00:20:18,129 --> 00:20:19,130
ANNIE: Oh.

404
00:20:19,783 --> 00:20:21,916
Do you like it?

405
00:20:21,959 --> 00:20:24,614
I love it.
I really love it.

406
00:20:24,658 --> 00:20:27,313
Do you want one?Oh, I'd love one, Sam.

407
00:20:27,356 --> 00:20:28,792
But it can't say "Mom."

408
00:20:28,836 --> 00:20:30,359
GILLIAN: [CHUCKLES] All right.

409
00:20:32,231 --> 00:20:33,754
How did you make it?Hi.

410
00:20:33,797 --> 00:20:36,191
They have this machine that
can make any kind of button.

411
00:20:36,235 --> 00:20:39,368
That's great.Especially like these.

412
00:20:39,412 --> 00:20:41,979
ANNIE: Hi, honey,
how was your day?

413
00:20:42,023 --> 00:20:43,894
Did you have a good day?

414
00:20:43,938 --> 00:20:45,287
Did you make new friends?

415
00:20:45,331 --> 00:20:46,288
Yeah.

416
00:20:48,334 --> 00:20:49,552
That's nice, Sam.

417
00:20:50,858 --> 00:20:51,902
[KIDS LAUGHING]

418
00:20:54,688 --> 00:20:56,342
ANNIE: Okay, let's
go down the slide.

419
00:20:56,385 --> 00:20:57,647
Be careful.

420
00:21:02,696 --> 00:21:04,219
[LAUGHS] You go first.

421
00:21:07,309 --> 00:21:08,571
Hold on.

422
00:21:10,399 --> 00:21:11,879
[LAUGHS]

423
00:21:11,922 --> 00:21:13,315
Good job.

424
00:21:13,359 --> 00:21:14,534
Are you okay?

425
00:21:14,577 --> 00:21:15,709
Good.

426
00:21:17,406 --> 00:21:19,887
Mom.

427
00:21:19,930 --> 00:21:23,934
Maggie said I couldn't play
in the sandbox with her.

428
00:21:23,978 --> 00:21:26,328
You tell your sister
I said if she doesn't
stop saying that

429
00:21:26,372 --> 00:21:27,677
that she can't play
in the sandbox.

430
00:21:31,899 --> 00:21:34,031
Okay. She has to go
to the bathroom.

431
00:21:34,902 --> 00:21:36,338
I'll take her.

432
00:21:36,382 --> 00:21:37,644
I'll go with you.

433
00:21:39,210 --> 00:21:42,388
[SAM MUMBLES]

434
00:21:42,431 --> 00:21:44,259
Sam, we're going
to show Gillian
where the bathroom is.

435
00:21:44,303 --> 00:21:45,739
We'll be back
in one minute.

436
00:21:45,782 --> 00:21:47,262
It's okay,
I'll watch him.

437
00:21:49,046 --> 00:21:51,005
Thank you.Oh, that's all right.

438
00:21:51,048 --> 00:21:52,354
You from London, eh?

439
00:21:52,398 --> 00:21:54,225
Yes, are you
from London?

440
00:21:54,269 --> 00:21:55,705
Within the sound
of Bow Bells.

441
00:21:55,749 --> 00:21:57,446
I'm Peg.I'm Gillian.

442
00:21:58,404 --> 00:21:59,883
It's nice to meet you.

443
00:21:59,927 --> 00:22:01,407
SAM: Come on, Matt, let's go.

444
00:22:02,408 --> 00:22:03,539
Yeah.

445
00:22:04,888 --> 00:22:06,107
ANNIE: Do you
want a family?

446
00:22:06,150 --> 00:22:07,456
I think so.

447
00:22:08,849 --> 00:22:10,938
It's so odd to me.

448
00:22:10,981 --> 00:22:12,592
There are so many
people in the world
who live alone.

449
00:22:13,506 --> 00:22:14,594
It's just foreign to me.

450
00:22:15,899 --> 00:22:18,728
I've never been alone.

451
00:22:18,772 --> 00:22:21,078
The most alone
I've ever been was
on the flight here.

452
00:22:21,122 --> 00:22:22,645
I could never
have done that.

453
00:22:23,951 --> 00:22:24,952
Why did you?

454
00:22:26,693 --> 00:22:28,564
Partly for the money.

455
00:22:28,608 --> 00:22:29,783
Shh.And...

456
00:22:31,306 --> 00:22:33,264
Partly because
if I'd stayed at home

457
00:22:33,308 --> 00:22:35,963
I knew what my life
would be, more or less.

458
00:22:36,006 --> 00:22:37,399
Before I'd even lived it.

459
00:22:42,273 --> 00:22:43,492
We'll be right
here, honey.

460
00:22:45,276 --> 00:22:47,583
Uh, if you're not
going to use that...

461
00:22:48,584 --> 00:22:50,107
My daughter's in there.

462
00:22:50,151 --> 00:22:51,631
[CHUCKLES] Are you crazy?

463
00:22:57,811 --> 00:22:59,290
You got another kid?

464
00:23:16,177 --> 00:23:18,919
You think a dragon
could blow it down?

465
00:23:18,962 --> 00:23:20,311
Wouldn't the
soldiers stop him?

466
00:23:20,355 --> 00:23:22,226
They can't see him.

467
00:23:22,270 --> 00:23:23,489
The dragon's invisible?

468
00:23:23,532 --> 00:23:24,881
Mmm-hmm, like Maggie.

469
00:23:26,230 --> 00:23:27,841
Oh.

470
00:23:27,884 --> 00:23:29,451
Can you hear the dragon?

471
00:23:29,495 --> 00:23:31,758
Of course, when it's roaring.
I just can't see him.

472
00:23:34,543 --> 00:23:36,327
SAM: My mom can see Maggie.

473
00:23:36,371 --> 00:23:38,721
I do sometimes.

474
00:23:38,765 --> 00:23:40,549
But I always can hear her,

475
00:23:40,593 --> 00:23:42,812
and I always can feel her.

476
00:23:42,856 --> 00:23:44,771
Especially when
she punches me.

477
00:23:47,164 --> 00:23:48,992
Maggie's different.

478
00:24:25,986 --> 00:24:26,943
ANNIE: Hey, pretty.

479
00:24:29,163 --> 00:24:31,992
I can't believe
you guys actually
used to wear this stuff.

480
00:24:32,035 --> 00:24:34,037
Watch it.

481
00:24:34,081 --> 00:24:36,910
I never saw you
look like this.

482
00:24:36,953 --> 00:24:40,087
You and Dad should
go out some time
dancing or something.

483
00:24:40,130 --> 00:24:42,350
What, and leave
you guys alone?

484
00:24:42,393 --> 00:24:43,482
Are you nuts?

485
00:24:46,659 --> 00:24:48,182
My beautiful Rebecca.

486
00:24:57,452 --> 00:24:58,758
[DOC GIGGLES]

487
00:25:00,063 --> 00:25:01,717
Hey, are you still up?

488
00:25:01,761 --> 00:25:03,153
Bedtime, Doctor.

489
00:25:03,197 --> 00:25:04,677
Oh, come on.
Let me have one
more chapter.

490
00:25:04,720 --> 00:25:05,982
Uh-uh-uh.Please, please, please.

491
00:25:06,896 --> 00:25:07,810
Bedtime.

492
00:25:09,943 --> 00:25:11,031
Okay.

493
00:25:11,074 --> 00:25:12,293
Good night.Good night.

494
00:25:17,864 --> 00:25:19,518
Good night.Good night.

495
00:25:23,434 --> 00:25:24,174
[GIGGLES]

496
00:25:25,741 --> 00:25:27,351
It still looks like
a bicycle rack.

497
00:25:28,048 --> 00:25:28,831
Really?

498
00:25:29,615 --> 00:25:30,746
[CHUCKLES]

499
00:25:32,618 --> 00:25:34,881
Does Sam seem like
he's coming down
with something?

500
00:25:34,924 --> 00:25:36,883
Mmm-hmm.
He caught it from Maggie.

501
00:25:38,798 --> 00:25:39,842
Right.

502
00:25:44,673 --> 00:25:46,719
You were going to say...

503
00:25:46,762 --> 00:25:48,851
[SIGHS] Nothing.

504
00:25:48,895 --> 00:25:49,939
I'm just thinking.

505
00:25:51,158 --> 00:25:52,159
About Gillian?

506
00:25:53,682 --> 00:25:56,555
It's been three weeks.

507
00:25:56,598 --> 00:25:58,818
And every time she takes
Sam and Maggie to school,

508
00:25:58,861 --> 00:26:00,907
she just opens the door
and lets them out.

509
00:26:00,950 --> 00:26:02,604
As opposed to...

510
00:26:02,648 --> 00:26:03,779
Walking them in.

511
00:26:05,651 --> 00:26:06,956
How do you know?

512
00:26:07,000 --> 00:26:08,349
'Cause I've been
following her.

513
00:26:11,526 --> 00:26:12,571
Oh.

514
00:26:16,139 --> 00:26:17,010
[SIGHS]

515
00:26:19,142 --> 00:26:20,274
Other than that?

516
00:26:20,970 --> 00:26:22,232
She's great.

517
00:26:27,716 --> 00:26:28,978
WOMAN: That's good.

518
00:26:32,808 --> 00:26:35,724
Now, over there, we have
the little tart, Caroline.

519
00:26:35,768 --> 00:26:37,813
She's a Georgia peach.

520
00:26:37,857 --> 00:26:39,641
Pit, that is.

521
00:26:39,685 --> 00:26:42,688
Spends most of her time in the
pool with her guv's stepson.

522
00:26:42,731 --> 00:26:44,994
And there's Ramona,
over there.

523
00:26:45,038 --> 00:26:47,083
No, I told you
not to let go!

524
00:26:47,127 --> 00:26:49,608
PEG: She's Romanian,
nanny for life.

525
00:26:49,651 --> 00:26:50,739
Rules the roost.

526
00:26:50,783 --> 00:26:52,785
Temper on her like
you won't believe.

527
00:26:52,828 --> 00:26:54,090
They love her.

528
00:26:54,134 --> 00:26:55,526
They bought her a house.

529
00:26:56,353 --> 00:26:57,790
